LOL, I've seen a lot of celebrity walk-in-wardrobe reactions, and most of the reactions/comments I've watched is that Heart doesn't "like" to show enough designer stuff, unlike the Kardashians who love to flaunt their wealth. And this equates to boring videos. Heart is exactly how a typical rich person (from an old-rich family) lives - by being low-key discreet. This is especially true for many East and SE Asian rich families. And old money rich doesn't like showy, in-your-face-logos shoes, bags and clothes. And they do love reasonably-priced and quality stuff like us normal people. I used to work in the company of Singapore's richest man - and we often encounter him, and his children during working. I'm from the East Coast US, but lived in Southeast Asia for a few years. And yes, your friend from Hong Kong is right. It gets extremely humid to the point where you can feel the moisture in the air on your skin standing still. Where I lived the locals had what they referred to as 120 days of summer, which described a period of roughly 4 months where it consistently got to between 100 - 120 degrees Fahrenheit and we would get intense tropical storms that lasted up to a week frequently. The combination of heat and humidity during that time changed the way most of us dressed. We did our best to avoid cotton or heavy, unbreathable fabrics. I wore a lot of thin, moisture wicking materials in both natural and artificial materials. You also knew not to wear something you would not be comfortable risking sweat stains or swamp pits in.

Â @ameliap0nddÂ  In a Filipino or Southeast Asian household, comfort is always put over lavishness. Many then-colonized Southeast Asian countries are considered third-world, and we have a very unstable economy, which is why money should always go to comfort and security. Many rich SEAsians invest in businesses because they would secure their wealth for the next generations to live a similarly comfortable life because most of the people who began the wealthy dynasties used to be in the working class. With the importance of family history, the unstable economy of the country, and the future of the family in mind, practicality is a must. Yes, they would enjoy luxuries at times because it's their right, they have the money for it, but they also have the responsibility to keep their wealth stable. Another thing why SOME rich people choose to live simply is because it helps them connect with their heritage and tradition deeper, which is an important part in Asian lives.

I work as an artist and in my gallery exhibits, I get to know who's old and new money right away. Mind you, I'm Asian but NOT rich, just a thriving artist. New money shows it loud, it has to be some recognizable high-end brand, I see them in shows. Old money like Heart and her husband are more subtle and they actually buy stuff from cheaper stores. The importance for them is how the clothes work for them rather than what the brand is. So yeah, I have an old money friend who loves shopping at Zara, H&M and Uniqlo and even go with me to Salvation Army finds. And they just live the moment when they find an authentic McQueen shoe for like $20 (Php1000)  in those heaps of surplus boots, it's almost funny. xD Also, framed Hermes scarves has been a thing for collectors. It's also a really great idea.
